i386/tcg: add Cyrix MediaGX 0F 3x decoder + 0F 3C compatibility shim (Pinball 2000).

Per the Cyrix MediaGX Processor Data Book v2.0, section 4.1.5 (Display
Driver Instructions) + Table 4-6, the MediaGX defines four documented
opcodes in the 0F 3x slot space:

  0F 3A  BB0_RESET   reset BLT-buffer-0 pointer
  0F 3B  BB1_RESET   reset BLT-buffer-1 pointer
  0F 3C  CPU_WRITE   EBX = internal-CPU-register addr; EAX = data
  0F 3D  CPU_READ    EBX = internal-CPU-register addr; EAX = data

Per section 4.1.6 they are gated on GCR (index B8h) bits[3:2] —
SCRATCHPAD_SIZE — and should #UD when that field is zero.

  Datasheet: https://datasheets.chipdb.org/Cyrix/MediaGX/gxmdb_v20.pdf

This patch is the *instrumentation + shim* step, not the full MediaGX
implementation. It adds:

  1. A runtime gate `p2k_mediagx_extensions_enabled` (defined and
     toggled by the pinball2000 machine in qemu/p2k-mediagx-gate.c).
     Default FALSE, so a stock qemu-system-i386 run is unaffected.

  2. Two TCG helpers in target/i386/tcg/misc_helper.c:
       helper_p2k_mediagx_log_0f3x_shim  — used by the 0F 3C shim
         entry. If gate FALSE, raises #UD (preserving stock behavior).
         If gate TRUE, logs a rate-limited line with EIP / EAX / EBX /
         ECX / EDX / EFLAGS and returns so the shim store can run.
       helper_p2k_mediagx_log_0f3x_ud    — used by the observation
         entries (0F 36/37/39/3B/3D/3F). Logs only when the gate is
         TRUE, then *always* raises #UD. Stock behavior is unchanged
         for these slots since they were #UD already.

  3. New decoder entries in target/i386/tcg/decode-new.c.inc:
       [0x36], [0x37], [0x39], [0x3b], [0x3d], [0x3f]  — observation
       [0x3c]                                          — shim

     0F 38 and 0F 3a are deliberately NOT touched: they are the SSSE3
     and SSE4.1+ escape prefixes for the 3-byte opcode map, and we
     must not break SSE4 dispatch on stock i386. The MediaGX-doc
     mapping of 0F 3A = BB0_RESET cannot be honoured at the same time
     as SSE4 prefix dispatch; if a real BB0_RESET implementation is
     ever needed for Pinball 2000, it will require a separate decoder
     hook gated on the runtime flag, splitting the slot into "MediaGX
     mode" vs "SSE4 prefix mode". Pinball 2000's XINU has not been
     observed to issue 0F 3A so this is deferred.

  4. `gen_CYRIX_0F3C_shim` in emit.c.inc reproduces the observable side
     effect of the legacy Unicorn / low-RAM IDT[6] stub the Pinball
     2000 XINU bring-up code relied on:

         [DS:EDX]   := EAX        ; 32-bit
         [DS:EDX+4] := EBX        ; 32-bit
         EDX        += 8

     This is NOT the documented CPU_WRITE semantics (EBX as internal-
     register address). It is a compatibility shim — sufficient for
     the boot matrix because XINU's 0F 3C users only rely on this
     pointer-walk pattern, not on MediaGX internal-register state.
     Real CPU_WRITE/READ + BB0/BB1_RESET semantics are the long-term
     direction (tracked in qemu/NOTES.next.md).

Without the gate, any stock qemu-system-i386 run that hit 0F 3C would
have run our shim store, which is wrong outside the pinball2000
machine. The gate restores stock #UD behavior.

Long-term direction (tracked in NOTES.next.md):
  * Implement real CPU_WRITE / CPU_READ semantics with EBX as internal-
    register address; model the few CPU-internal registers Pinball 2000
    actually touches (BLT buffer base/pointer, GP-DMA descriptors).
  * Implement BB0_RESET / BB1_RESET if/when the guest actually issues
    them (currently neither has been observed; the new log entries
    will tell us for sure).
  * Honour the GCR[B8h] SCRATCHPAD_SIZE gate via qemu/p2k-cyrix-ccr.c
    so the documented #UD-when-disabled behavior is preserved.
  * Resolve the 0F 3A vs SSE4-prefix collision properly if a guest
    issuance of 0F 3A is observed.


